Comment:
Hate to ramble, but it would have to be one hell of a virus to not only alter but maintain all the chemical and biological changes required to make a typical zombie. Viruses usually just disrupt cells by causing them to produce junk. The resulting conditions depend on what cells are being damaged.

You COULD argue that a virus can disrupt the production and regulation of certain proteins and hormones, making the host go crazier than a shithouse rat, but infected would attack each other, too.

Comment: While these behaviors look very intelligent, they’re really a different kind of intelligence that emerges at a macro scale from micro-scale, or local, interactions. It’s like when you see a flock of birds or a school of fish all turning together: There’s not an organizing intelligence directing them all where to go; rather, each individual is tuned in to its nearest neighbors.

Comment: The behavior can be akin to those insects, which work together to take down much bigger spiders or build bridges across large bodies of water. Honestly, if it wasn't based on the novel, I'd have no major problem with it, but Max Brooks must be pissed right now.

As a rule, people tend to use trailers to form a preliminary judgement about whether or not they will be able to enjoy a movie. Is it fair to judge a movie by the trailer?
